FT  21 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics in Brief
HOUSING: Mr Neil Kinnock, Labour leader, yesterday called on the government
to implement a phased release of capital receipts held by local authorities
as a means of stimulating house building.
He also urged the government to set up a National Housing Investment Bank.
*****
IRELAND: Amendment of the Irish Republic's constitutional claim on Northern
Ireland was 'a matter for the republic' but could be discussed if
'round-table' talks were restarted, Mr John Major told MPs. He reaffirmed
the government's commitment to the 1985 Anglo-Irish Agreement, 'unless and
until agreement can be reached on new and more broadly satisfactory
arrangements'.
*****
SUNDAY TRADING: Mrs Angela Rumbold, Home Office minister, made it clear that
the government would oppose a private member's bill to reform the Sunday
trading laws introduced by Mr Ray Powell (Lab Ogmore), who is sponsored by
Usdaw, the shop workers' union.
*****
CAR CRIME: Insurance companies were urged to do 'very much more' to help
combat car crime by Mr Kenneth Baker, home secretary, yesterday. Mr William
Hague (C Richmond N Yorks) said there should be lower premiums for owners
who improved vehicle security.
